TypeScript is a statically typed, open-source programming language developed and maintained by Microsoft. It is a superset of JavaScript, meaning that any valid JavaScript code is also valid TypeScript code. TypeScript adds several features to JavaScript, including optional static typing, interfaces, classes, and modules. These features aim to improve code quality, maintainability, and developer productivity by catching type-related errors during development and providing better tooling support, such as code completion, refactoring, and type checking.

Static typing in TypeScript allows developers to declare the types of variables, function parameters, and return types. This helps in catching type-related errors at compile-time, making the code more robust and easier to understand. TypeScript also has a type system that supports structural typing, a form of duck typing. Duck typing is a concept where an object's type is determined by the presence of certain methods and properties, rather than its class or interface. In TypeScript, this means that two types are considered compatible if they have the same set of properties and methods, regardless of their declared type.

Here's an example to illustrate duck typing in TypeScript using interfaces:

```typescript
interface Quackable {
  quack(): void;
}

class Duck implements Quackable {
  quack() {
    console.log("Quack!");
  }
}

class NotADuck {
  quack() {
    console.log("I'm quacking like a duck!");
  }
}

function makeItQuack(duck: Quackable) {
  duck.quack();
}

let duck = new Duck();
let notADuck = new NotADuck();

makeItQuack(duck);      // OK, Duck implements Quackable interface
makeItQuack(notADuck);  // Also OK, NotADuck has a quack method
```

In this example, both the `Duck` and `NotADuck` classes have a `quack` method, even though they are not related by inheritance. The `makeItQuack` function requires an argument that conforms to the `Quackable` interface, which only specifies that the object must have a `quack` method. Both classes satisfy this requirement, so TypeScript allows them to be passed to the `makeItQuack` function.

In summary, TypeScript combines the benefits of static typing, such as improved code quality and better tooling, with a form of duck typing through its structural typing system. This combination enables developers to write code that is more robust, maintainable, and interoperable while maintaining the flexibility of dynamically typed languages like JavaScript.

To create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a single slash command named `ban`, follow these steps:

1. First, make sure you have Node.js installed on your system. You can download it from the [official website](https://nodejs.org/).
2. Create a new directory for your bot project and navigate to it in the terminal or command prompt.
3. Run `npm init -y` to create a `package.json` file.
4. Install Discord.js v14 by running `npm install discord.js@14`.
5. Create a new file called `bot.js` and open it in a text editor.
6. Add the following code to `bot.js`:

```javascript
// Import required packages
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, SlashCommandBuilder, PermissionsBitField } = require('discord.js');

// Replace these with your own bot's token and guild ID
const botToken = 'your-bot-token-here';
const guildId = 'your-guild-id-here';

// Create the Discord client
const client = new Client({ intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages, GatewayIntentBits.MessageContent] });

// Define the ban command
const banCommand = new SlashCommandBuilder()
  .setName('ban')
  .setDescription('Bans a member from the server.')
  .addUserOption(option => option.setName('user').setDescription('The member to ban'))
  .addStringOption(option => option.setName('reason').setDescription('The reason for the ban (optional)'));

// Register the command
const commands = [
  banCommand.build(),
];

const rest = new client.api.rest.REST({ version: '9' }).setToken(botToken);

(async () => {
  try {
    console.log('Registering application commands.');
    await rest.put(
      client.api.applications(client.user.id).guilds(guildId).commands,
      { body: commands },
    );
    console.log('Successfully registered application commands.');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
})();

// Handle the ban command
client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
    const userToBan = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

    if (!interaction.member.permissions.has(PermissionsBitField.Flags.BanMembers)) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'You do not have permission to ban members.', ephemeral: true });
    }

    if (interaction.member.id === userToBan.id) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'You cannot ban yourself!', ephemeral: true });
    }

    try {
      await interaction.guild.members.ban(userToBan, { reason });
      interaction.reply({ content: `Successfully banned \`${userToBan.tag}\` for \`${reason}\`.` });
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
      interaction.reply({ content: 'There was an error banning the member!', ephemeral: true });
    }
  }
});

// Login the bot
client.login(botToken);
```

Replace `'your-bot-token-here'` with your bot's token, which you can find in the Discord Developer Portal (create an app, then go to Bot > Token). Also, replace `'your-guild-id-here'` with the ID of the guild where you want to register the slash command.

7. Run your bot with `node bot.js`.

Now, when you run the `/ban` command in your Discord server, the bot will prompt you to select a user and provide a reason (optional). It will then ban the selected user if the member running the command has the "Ban Members" permission.

Here's a C++ function that converts a subset of Markdown formatted text to HTML formatted text. This implementation handles basic Markdown features such as headings, bold, italic, links, and unordered lists. It uses C++11's `<regex>` library for pattern matching and replacement. Please note that for a comprehensive solution, you might want to consider using dedicated Markdown parsing libraries like `cmark` or `markdown-cpp`.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Headings
    html = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex(R"(^# (.*$))"), "<h1>$1</h1>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(^## (.*$))"), "<h2>$1</h2>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(^### (.*$))"), "<h3>$1</h3>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(^#### (.*$))"), "<h4>$1</h4>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(^##### (.*$))"), "<h5>$1</h5>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(^###### (.*$))"), "<h6>$1</h6>");

    // Bold
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(\*\*(.+?)\*\*)"), "<strong>$1</strong>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(__(.+?)__)"), "<strong>$1</strong>");

    // Italic
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(\*(.+?)\*)"), "<em>$1</em>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(_(.+?)_)"), "<em>$1</em>");

    // Links
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(\[(.+?)\]\((.+?)\))"), "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");

    // Unordered lists
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(^\s*\* (.*$))"), "<ul><li>$1</li></ul>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(^\s*-\s+(.*$))"), "<ul><li>$1</li></ul>");

    // Paragraphs
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"((?:\r?\n){2,})"), "</p><p>");
    html = "<p>" + html + "</p>";

    // Trim leading and trailing whitespace
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(R"(^\s+|\s+$)"), "");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown =
        "# Heading 1\n"
        "## Heading 2\n"
        "### Heading 3\n"
        "\n"
        "This is **bold** and _italic_ text.\n"
        "[Link text](http://example.com)\n"
        "\n"
        "* List item 1\n"
        "* List item 2\n"
        "\n"
        "Another paragraph.";

    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This function converts basic Markdown elements to HTML. However, it doesn't handle more complex features like code blocks, blockquotes, or escaped characters. For a complete Markdown to HTML conversion, consider using a dedicated library.

